  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN145.1-kilavi">makaṭpōkkiya cevilittāy colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">What the foster mother said who had let [her] daughter go.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="AN145.1">
              <l><anchor n="1"/>vērmuḻu tulaṟi niṉṟa puḻaṟkāṟ</l>
              <l>ṟērmaṇi <supplied>yi</supplied>caiyiṟ ciḷvī ṭārkkum</l>
              <l>vaṟṟaṉ maratta poṟṟalai yō<supplied>ti</supplied></l>
              <l>veyiṟkavi ṉiḻanta vaip<supplied>pi</supplied>ṟ paiyuḷkoḷa</l>
              <l>nuṇṇiti ṉiḷakkum veṇñemai viyaṉkāṭ</l>
              <l>ṭāḷi lattan tamiya ḷavaṉoṭu</l>
              <l>vāḷvari poruta puṇkūr yāṉaip</l>
              <l>pukarcitai mukatta kuruti vāra</l>
              <l>vuyarcimai neṭuṅkōṭ ṭurumeṉa muḻaṅku</l>
              <l>maruñcura miṟantaṉa ḷeṉpa peruñ<supplied>cī</supplied></l>
              <l>raṉṉik kuṟukkaip paṟantalait titiyaṉ</l>
              <l>ṟoṉṉilai muḻumuta ṟu<supplied>mi</supplied>yap paṇṇiya</l>
              <l>naṉṉar me<supplied>lli</supplied>ṇarp puṉṉai pōlan</l>
              <l>tavintavaip paṭiyar mātō kali<supplied>mayil</supplied></l>
              <l>kuñcarak kurala kurukō ṭālun</l>
              <l>tuñcā muḻaviṟ ṟuyakkiyal vāṭkaik</l>
              <l>kūḻuṭait tantai yiṭaṉuṭai varaippi</l>
              <l>ṉūḻaṭi yotuṅkiṉu muyaṅku maimpāṟ</l>
              <l>ciṟupal kūntaṟ pōtuppiṭit taruḷā</l>
              <l>terikōl citaiya nūṟavuñ ciṟupuṟa</l>
              <l>meṉakkurit teṉṉā ṇiṉṟave</l>
              <l>ṉamarkkaṇ maññaiyai<anchor n="2"/> yalaitta kaiyē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>She alone with him on a road devoid of men, (6)</l>
                <l>in the wide wilderness of Ñemai trees, (5cd)</l>
                <l>where the golden-headed lizard on the desiccated tree, (3)</l>
                <l>in which crickets sound like the tones of chariot bells, (2)</l>
                <l>with a tubular trunk that stands completely dried, down to the root, (1)</l>
                <l>in the region that lost [its] beauty in the sunlight, sorrowfully (4)</l>
                <l rend="indent8">[and] subtly shakes itself, (5ab)</l>
                <l>she has gone to traverse the difficult desert, they say, (10a-c)</l>
                <l>where the wound-covered elephant that fought the one with sickle-stripes (7)</l>
                <l>thunders tumultuously on the long peaks of the high summits (9)</l>
                <l>while blood in [its] face flows over, spoiling [his face] spots. (8)</l>
                <l>Like the mastwood tree with good, soft clusters (13)</l>
                <l>made by Titiyaṉ, when [its] whole base, its ancient foothold, was cut down</l>
                <l>by Aṉṉi of great fame, in the waste lands of Kuṟukkai, thus (10d-12)</l>
                <l>let them suffer, being thus under control, (14a-c)</l>
                <l>– the hands that slapped my peacock [daughter] with beautiful eyes (22)</l>
                <l>who stood there, not one to say “this is not right by me”, (21)</l>
                <l>even though [I] beat the small of [her] back painfully with a fiery stick, (20)</l>
                <l>without compunction gripping the buds in the many small tresses (19)</l>
                <l>of [her, wearing her hair] in five parts, who became weak when [her] feet took one turn (18)</l>
                <l>from the boundaries of [her] affluent father’s place, (17)</l>
                <l>with a living of desirable nature, with drums that do not sleep, (16)</l>
                <l>to which bustling peacocks dance, elephant-voiced, along with the herons. (14df.)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>

